  }, "https://ribbonfarm.com/2018/02/15/make-your-own-rules")), mdx("hr", null), mdx("p", null, "I\u2019ve never actually been able to use any life rule set for its nominal purpose."), mdx("p", null, "I\u2019d be hard pressed to even enumerate any of the sets I\u2019ve encountered in full."), mdx("p", null, "The famous ones are more memorization challenges for trivia contests than operating systems that can be encoded in neural firmware as embodied virtues. They aren\u2019t routinely helpful in navigating the ambiguities and uncertainties of life. Nor do they set meaningfully universal go/no-go boundaries."), mdx("p", null, "They do not, in other words, constitute clean MECE (mutually exclusive, collectively exhaustive) coverage of the messiness of life, capable of bringing order to chaos in any sort of guaranteed way."), mdx("hr", null), mdx("p", null, " Life rule sets are about governing task-negative cognition."), mdx("hr", null), mdx("p", null, "Where\xA0does\xA0the mind wander?"), mdx("p", null, "The literature on the default mode network seems to indicate the following default inner dialogue conversation topics for the DMN:"), mdx("p", null, "Autobiographical thinking (reflecting on your life)\nThinking about relationships (other-regarding cognitions including envy, admiration etc)\nWhat-if ruminations about the future\nCreative-play imaginative thinking\nIdle day-dreaming exploring pleasing thoughts\nAspects of sleep dreaming\nAnxious, obsessive thoughts about non-clear-and-present threats\nUnfocused attention (scanning the environment)\nWhat is common to all these themes is that they involve things you care about, but lack sufficient information, agency, computational tractability, or environmental enabling conditions to act on. You can\u2019t be task-positive about them. There\u2019s nothing to\xA0do\xA0immediately,\xA0only stuff to think about."), mdx("hr", null), mdx("p", null, "The most basic distinction in how the DMN ruminates is between\xA0other-regarding cognitions (thoughts about other people) and\xA0material cognitions"), mdx("hr", null), mdx("p", null, "To enter the triangle is to compromise priceless principles, exit finite games, and deal with the open-ended possibilities of being by testing yourself against open-ended realities."), mdx("hr", null), mdx("p", null, "The universe contains infinities, and one way or another, you\u2019ll be forced to deal with them. You can have priceless values, or unbounded possibilities, but not both. So rules 1 and 3 are infinite-game rules (and also rules about how noble Klingons ought to deal with markets and evil Ferengi traders) while rules 2 and 4 are finite-game rules, governing interactions with people who generally share your basic ideas about what is priceless (what I\u2019ve called saint-saint as opposed to saint-trader interactions, see also my Principia Misanthropica)."), mdx("ul", null, mdx("li", {
